<section class="section section--alt" id="kitchen-sink-d3-state-pillar-context">
  <div class="container">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">Why New York is different</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">What makes New York accounting different.</h2>
      <p class="section__lede">New York&rsquo;s tax structure, industry concentration, and operational profile create accounting requirements that don&rsquo;t look like any other state. Generic out-of-state bookkeeping &mdash; or bookkeepers unfamiliar with the NYC layer &mdash; misses what matters most.</p>
    </header>
    <div class="grid-2">
      <div class="stack-8">
        <p class="section__eyebrow">Income Tax Stack</p>
        <h3>Highest combined rate in the U.S.</h3><p class="prose">New York City residents face <strong>federal + NY State + NYC personal income tax</strong>, with a combined top marginal rate of <strong>14.776%</strong> (10.9% NY State + 3.876% NYC). NY State also levies a <strong>Metropolitan Commuter Transportation Mobility Tax (MCTMT)</strong> on net earnings from self-employment in the Metro area.</p><p class="prose"><strong>QuickBooks Payroll must be configured for both NY State and NYC withholding</strong> for each NYC-resident employee. Missing the NYC layer is a common payroll error for businesses new to the city. <a href="/find-an-accountant/new-york/state-tax-notice-help/">NY tax notice detail &rarr;</a></p>
      </div>
      <div class="stack-8">
        <p class="section__eyebrow">NYC Unincorporated Business Tax</p>
        <h3>The UBT catches growing firms off guard.</h3><p class="prose">The <strong>NYC UBT</strong> applies to unincorporated businesses &mdash; sole proprietors and partnerships &mdash; doing business in the five boroughs. At <strong>4% on net income attributable to NYC</strong>, it is invisible until a firm grows or incorporates improperly.</p><p class="prose">Allocation of NYC-sourced vs. non-NYC income must be tracked in QuickBooks from the first transaction. Retroactive cleanup is common and expensive. <a href="/find-an-accountant/new-york/state-tax-notice-help/">UBT planning detail &rarr;</a></p>
      </div>
      <div class="stack-8">
        <p class="section__eyebrow">Sales Tax on Services</p>
        <h3>8.875% in NYC &mdash; applied to services other states don&rsquo;t tax.</h3><p class="prose">New York taxes a wider range of services than most states &mdash; information services, certain cleaning services, parking, interior design, and more. The <strong>combined NYC rate of 8.875%</strong> (state + city + MTA) applies and must be correctly configured per service type in QuickBooks.</p><p class="prose">Agencies and media firms often have mixed taxable and exempt revenue on the same invoice. Getting it wrong triggers NY DTF notices. <a href="/find-an-accountant/new-york/sales-tax-help/">NY sales tax detail &rarr;</a></p>
      </div>
      <div class="stack-8">
        <p class="section__eyebrow">Industry Profile</p>
        <h3>Financial services, agencies, law, nonprofits &mdash; and upstate manufacturing.</h3><p class="prose">NYC&rsquo;s economy is dominated by <strong>financial services, agencies, media, real estate, legal, and healthcare</strong>. Upstate New York &mdash; Buffalo, Rochester, Syracuse &mdash; adds <strong>manufacturing, construction, and agriculture</strong>.</p><p class="prose">Each vertical has distinct QuickBooks requirements: IOLTA trust ledgers for law firms, CHAR500-ready workpapers for nonprofits, gross-vs-net revenue recognition for agencies, job costing for construction.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="prose"><small>New York operational context informs every TechBrot engagement in the state. The diagnostic call identifies which factors apply to your business.</small></p>
